Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** that can be dropped into an OCaml project and compiled with the usual `ocamlfind`/`ocamlc`/`ocamlopt` tool‑chain (you only have to add the C++ source to the build command and link with `-lstdc++`).  

The binding

* wraps a C++ `pcapng::File` object in a custom OCaml block (`type t`);
* exposes a *record* type `frame` that contains the four fields the iterator yields;
* provides two iteration entry points  
  – `iter_frames` (high‑level, returns a `frame` record)  
  – `iter_frames_raw` (low‑level, passes the four fields directly, avoiding the record allocation);
* takes great care to keep the hot path fast:
  * the iterator runs completely in C++ – the only OCaml‑side work is a single callback per frame;
  * the frame payload is exposed as a **bigarray** that points directly to the memory owned by libpcapng (no copy);
  * the callback is invoked with `caml_callback_exn`; if the OCaml callback raises, the exception is propagated immediately;
  * the custom block for `t` has a finaliser that deletes the C++ object, so there is no memory leak;
  * the code is written with the OCaml “C‑macro” API (`CAMLparam`, `CAMLlocal`, …) so the GC sees the temporaries correctly.

---

## 1. The public OCaml interface – **`pcapng.mli`**

```ocaml
(* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   pcapng.mli – public interface for the libpcapng OCaml binding
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- *)

(** Opaque handle to a pcapng file. *)
type t

(** A single frame as returned by the iterator.

    The payload is a bigarray that points directly to the memory managed by
    libpcapng; it must **not** be kept after the callback returns. *)
type frame = {
  ts     : int64;                                         (* timestamp, ns *)
  caplen : int;                                          (* captured length *)
  len    : int;                                          (* original length *)
  data   : (char, Bigarray.c_layout) Bigarray.Array1.t; (* payload *)
}

(** Open a pcapng file.  Raises [Invalid_argument] if the file cannot be
    opened or parsed. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Close the file and free the underlying C++ object.  After this call the
    handle must not be used again. *)
val close : t -> unit

(** Iterate over all frames, calling the supplied OCaml function for each
    frame.  The callback receives a fresh {!frame} record each time; the
    record is freed as soon as the callback returns, so the payload must not
    be stored beyond the call.  The iteration is *fast*: the only OCaml work
    per frame is the construction of the record and the callback invocation.
    If the callback raises an exception the iteration stops and the same
    exception is propagated to the caller. *)
val iter_frames : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit

(** Low‑level variant that avoids allocating a {!frame} record.  The callback
    receives the four fields directly.  This is the fastest possible entry
    point for hot‑code paths.

    The bigarray payload has the same lifetime rules as in {!frame}. *)
val iter_frames_raw :
  t ->
  (int64 ->               (* ts *)
   int ->                 (* caplen *)
   int ->                 (* len *)
   (char, Bigarray.c_layout) Bigarray.Array1.t ->   (* data *)
   unit) ->
  unit
```

